===Adjective===
{{en-adj|-}}

# {{context|Scotland|and|Northern England|lang=en}} The [[same]].
#: {{rfquotek|Spenser}}

====Usage notes====
Used following a person’s name to show that he lives in a place of the same name, eg ''Johnstone of that ilk'' means ''Johnstone of Johnstone''.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[type]], [[race]] or [[category]]; a group of entities that have common characteristics such that they may be grouped together.
#* {{RQ:Sinclair Jungle|25}}
#*: "Hinkydink” or “Bathhouse John,” or others of that '''ilk''', were proprietors of the most notorious dives in Chicago{{...}}

====Usage notes====
* In modern use, ''ilk'' is used in phrases such as ''of his ilk'', {{term|of that ilk}}, to mean ‘type’ or ‘sort.’ The use arose out of a misunderstanding of the earlier, Scottish use in the phrase ''of that ilk'', where it means ‘of the same name or place.’ For this reason, some traditionalists regard the modern use as incorrect. It is, however, the only common current use and is now part of standard English.
* ''[Proper noun] and ilk'' a usually disparaging phrase, perhaps a hendiadys, to mean ''people like [proper noun]''

